 Let the two positive integers be $x$ and $y$ with $x \geq y$. We have:
\begin{aligned} x-y &= 12 \\ xy &= 45 \end{aligned}
Let's think about how we can solve this pair of equations. Interestingly, this leads us to a method for solving a pair of equations of the form 
\begin{aligned} x-y &= a \\ xy &= b \end{aligned}
Our idea will be to make both equations quadratic equations and then solve. Observe:
\begin{aligned} (x-y)^2 &= 144 \\ x^2-2xy+y^2 &= 144 \\ x^2+y^2 &= 144 +2xy \\ x^2+y^2 &= 144 + 2 \times 45 \\ x^2+y^2 &= 234 \\ \end{aligned}
Quadratic equations are in the shape $(x+y)^2 = x^2 +y^2 + 2xy$. 
So $(x+y)^2 = 234 + 2 \times 45 = 324$. Hence $x+y$ can be found by taking square root. $x+y=18$
